# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trophic-cascade
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:trophic-cascade/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The radio art of Schafer and his colleague, has found expression in many different fields.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] While most have taken some inspiration from Schafer's writings, in recent years there have also been divergences from the initial ideas.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The expanded expressions of acoustic ecology are increasing due to the sonic impacts of road and airport construction that affect the soundscapes in and around cities where the human population is more dense.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] There has also been a broadening of bioacoustics (the use of sound by animals) to consider the subjective and objective responses of animals to human noise, with ocean noise capturing the most attention.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology can also be informative of changes in the climate or other environmental changes since every day we listen to sounds in the world to identify their source such as bird, car, plane, wind, water.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] But we don't listen those sounds as a network, a mesh of relationships that form an ecology.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology finds expression in many different fields that characterize a soundscape, which are biophony, geophony, and anthrophony.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Noise is generally a by-product of increased urbanization and development.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] As our cities became more industrialized, the volume and frequency of anthrophony, man-made noise signals, increased.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Noise can alter the acoustic environment of aquatic and terrestrial habitats.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Animal biodiversity has shown to decline because of chronic noise levels in cities and along roadways.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Musician and soundscape ecologist Bernie Krause relates biophony to an orchestra, where different groups of animals in an environment make sounds at different levels to avoid overlap or competition in their communication.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Manmade noise such as jets flying over a habitat can disrupt the natural order of these sounds, even putting certain species in danger of predators.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] For example, some frogs synchronize in a way that protects individuals from attracting attention.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The noise of a jet can cause the frogs to stop or fall out of sync, temporarily breaking this effect and exposing them to other animals.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] On land, animal communication is shaped by physical characteristics of an environment such as distance, range of vision, weather, and surrounding noise.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The physical layout of a habitat may impede the spread of soundwaves while air conditions can affect sound quality and speed.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Animals can adapt to factors like distance by adjusting the frequency and amplitute of their calls to maximize communication effectiveness.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Some species such as the urban great tits have changed the frequency of their calls to adapt.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes of particular habitats are always evolving because the activities and species that exist in those habitats changes over time.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] In terms of evolution, man-made noise is a much more recent phenomenon.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Indeed, through investigating collected recordings, ecologists can study ethology of animal acoustic communication, evolution, and development of acoustic behavior, relationships between animal sounds and their environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] However, all those ecological research goals have a precondition that those bioacoustic recordings are well investigated so that the animal species can be accurately recognized.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Scientific research has shown that it has potential to change behavior, alter physiology and even restructure animal communities.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Soundscapes are composed of the anthrophony, geophony and biophony of a particular environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] They are specific to location and change over time.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Acoustic ecology aims to study the relationship between these things, i.e. the relationship between humans, animals and nature, within these soundscapes.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] These relationships are delicate and subject to disruption by natural or man-made means.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] In his book *The Tuning of the World*, Schafer used new terms like 'soundmarks' -- a specific community's distinctive sounds—and 'keynotes' -- prevalent but overlooked background sounds such as traffic—to help categorize the different elements of a soundscape.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Biophony is the study of sounds emerging from animal sources, like whale vocalizations or birdsong.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Geophony can be defined as the sounds originating from the Earth's natural processes, such as the blowing of wind or movement of waves.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Anthrophony is the soundscape defined by man-made sources, like speech or road noise.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Research on the relationship between visual and auditory experiences in urban settings finds that the positive or negative visual perceptions of a landscape can directly affect the emotional assessment of the location's soundscape.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] A pleasant view or comfortable surroundings can increase people's tolerance and even appreciation for the sounds of an environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] People's preferences for noise control have been shown to differ based on the culture and technology of the time period as well as the familiarity or practicality of certain sounds.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] For example, accepted sources of loud noise such as church bells or trucks may not bother a neighborhood as much as someone's new leaf blower, even if it is not as loud as more familiar sounds.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] This is why it is considered difficult to generalize which sounds are unwanted in a community.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Studying the soundscapes and traumatic impact of war has shown the effectiveness of noise as a psychological weapon to produce fear.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Aircraft activity has been a continuing development around the world and has some very good potential to change social-ecological systems.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] In Alaska, for example the communities are reporting that the aircraft disturb wildlife and negatively influence harvest practices and experiences.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The limited data has some restricted knowledge about the extent of aircraft activity over traditional harvest areas.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] It is actually very impressive to see the amount of aircraft overflight around the rural subsistence, because the activity is increasing significantly and they have reached a median of 12 overflights per day near human development, which is six times greater than undeveloped areas.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Therefore, those planes startle caribou prefer to avoid aircraft themselves, which has a result that they will need to go farther to do a better harvest, but this will occur in adding some costs for fuel, equipment, and the effort for sure.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Those kind of examples help to understand the impact on social-ecological dynamics in Antarctica.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The ambient noise present within the world's oceans; geophonic, anthrophonic, and biophonic, has been identified as a critical indicator to the well-being of the regional biosphere.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The acoustic niche hypothesis, as proposed by acoustic ecologist Bernie Krause in 1993, refers to the process in which organisms partition the acoustic domain, finding their own niche in frequency and/or time in order to communicate without competition from other species.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The theory draws from the ideas of niche differentiation and can be used to predict differences between young and mature ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Similar to how interspecific competition can place limits on the number of coexisting species that can utilize a given availability of habitats or resources, the available acoustic space in an environment is a limited resource that is partitioned among those species competing to utilize it.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] In mature ecosystems, species will sing at unique bandwidths and specific times, displaying a lack of interspecies competition in the acoustic environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Conversely, in young ecosystems, one is more likely to encounter multiple species using similar frequency bandwidths, which can result in interference between their respective calls, or a complete lack of activity in uncontested bandwidths.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Biological invasions can also result in interference in the acoustic niche, with non-native species altering the dynamics of the native community by producing signals that mask or degrade native signals.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] This can cause a variety of ecological impacts, such as decreased reproduction, aggressive interactions, and altered predator-prey dynamics.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] The degree of partitioning in an environment can be used to indicate ecosystem health and biodiversity.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] "Dominion" uses Canadian soundmarks that were made in different province by the World Soundscape Project at Simon Fraser University for an event of cross-country tour that happened in 1973.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] What is interesting about those sounds is that they are stretched over the time, so the extended versions allowed the people that listen to the sound in a more harmonic way.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Those unique sound signals, were picked up by the live performers and then amplified to give the best experience possible to his audience.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] This is a subfield of archeology and acoustics that in general study the relation between people and sound along the history.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] This is an interdisciplinary field that has methodological contributions from acoustics, archeology and computer simulation.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Many cultures explored through archaeology were mostly focused on the oral, which lead the researchers to believe that studying the sonic nature of archaeological sites and artifacts may reveal new information on the civilization being scrutinized.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] Moglen (2007) recreated pre-historical Soundscapes (Acoustic Ecology) at University of California, Berkeley's Department of Anthropology, combining compositional techniques with site recordings for a non-diegetic piece in the virtual world of Second Life, on "Okapi Island" .
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-ecology] At the Center for New Media the acoustic ecological setting of the former jazz scene in Oakland, CA was developed for a virtual world setting.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags transmit a signal made up of acoustic pulses or "pings" that send positional information of the tagged organism to a hydrophone receiver.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] By tying the received acoustic frequency to a predetermined and unique signal code, tagged animals can be identified at an individual level.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Transmitted signals may propagate up to 1 km (in freshwater) depending on tag model and environmental conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Receivers can be actively held by a researcher ("Active Tracking") or affixed to specific locations ("Passive Tracking").
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Arrays of receivers can allow the triangulation of tagged individuals over many kilometers.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags are produced in many different shapes and sizes depending on the study organism or study environment.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] The battery life of acoustic tags varies by size, with some larger tags lasting over four years.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Sound parameters such as frequency and modulation method are chosen for optimal detectability and signal level.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] For oceanic environments, frequencies less than 100 kHz range are often used, while frequencies of several hundreds of kilohertz are more common in for studies in rivers and lakes.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] A typical acoustic tag consists of a piezoceramic transducer, drive/timing electronics, and a battery power source.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Cylindrical or “tube” transducers are often used, which have metalization on the inner and outer walls of the structure.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] In normal operation, an alternating current (AC) electrical signal generated by the drive/timing electronics is impressed across the two metalization layers.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] This voltage creates stress in the material, which in turn cause the transducer to emit an acoustic signal or “ping”, which emanates outward from the surface of the tube.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] An acoustic “ping” can be detected by specialized receivers, and processed using advanced signal processing techniques to determine if a fish swimming into the reception area carries a specific acoustic tag.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Several different methods are used to attach the tag to an organism.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] In fish, tags are frequently surgically implanted in the abdominal cavity.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Surgical implantation generally results in high tag retention, therefore it is regularly used.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Electro-immobilization with a TENS unit and chemical immobilization with compounds such as eugenol are commonly used to restrict fish movement during surgery.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] In some instances, tags are endogastrically implanted by forcing the tag down the gullet.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags may also be attached externally using additional braces or tag types.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] By determining the sound's time of arrival at each hydrophone, the 3D position of the fish can be calculated.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] The hydrophone receiver picks up the sound signal and converts it to data that researchers use to plot the resulting tag positions in three dimensions, in real-time.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Using a post processing software, such as *MarkTags*, takes that data and delivers the result, the 3D track.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] At present, acoustic tags are most commonly used to monitor fish approaching diversion and guidance structures at hydropower dams.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Ultimately, working to improve bypass effectiveness and protect fish populations, Acoustic Tag Tracking Systems are a significant breakthrough in the preservation of migrating salmon populations.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags have been employed to help public utility agencies, private firms, and state and federal agencies meet fisheries regulations as defined by the Federal Regulations and Oversight of Energy (FERC Archived 2020-06-15 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] In the Laurentian Great Lakes, acoustic telemetry has addressed a variety of fishery research and management concerns through research conducted through the Great Lakes Acoustic Telemetry Observation System (GLATOS).
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Estimates of spawning site fidelity have been made for lake trout and walleye.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic telemetry has also been used to inform invasive species management through the use of *Judas fish*, or tagged fish used to "betray" the location or behaviors of others.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Acoustic tags were used on sea lamprey in the Great Lakes to determine the effectiveness of traps at physical removal and to locate potential spawning locations.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] They have also been used on common carp throughout North America to identify seasonal aggregations for future exploitation and removal.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Although incredibly valuable as a research and management tool, acoustic tags have some limitations.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Foremost, the equipment required for acoustic telemetry (*e.g.*, tags, receivers, replacement batteries for receivers, mounting and deployment materials for receivers) can be cost-prohibitive especially in comparison to other techniques such as radio telemetry.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] For example, acoustic receivers can cost more than US$2,000 per unit while tags can range from $200 - US$1,000 per unit, depending on model.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Additionally, acoustic tags have variable detection range depending on habitat type, tag size, and environmental conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Variability in detection or poor detection probability could ultimately influence conclusions made from data and therefore is important to account for by range testing.
[src:trophic-cascade/acoustic-tag] Considerations on project scale and timeframe are necessary before implementing acoustic telemetry.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to model population structures of many species including vertebrates, invertebrates, and vegetation.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Factors that influence age class structures include birth rates, death rates, migration, and environmental stressors.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] These models allow for the prediction of growth or decline in a population based on current conditions or future management practices.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Age class structures can be used to help focus management on a certain age class to obtain the desires population size outcomes.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Individuals in a population that are within a certain age range belong to the same class.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] These age classes count age like we usually do: individuals who are less than 1 year old are considered age class 0, those who are at least one year old but not yet two are age 1, and so on.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] When individuals are sorted into age classes like this, we can describe the population's age structure - meaning how many individuals are in each age group.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Imagine a species where no one lives past 3 years old.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This means all individuals would be either less than 1 year old (age class 0), 2 years old (age class 1), or 3 years old (age class 2).
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Therefore, if there are 20 individuals in total - 4 are newborns, 6 are 1-year-olds, and 10 are 2-year-olds - then the age structure would be 0.2 in age class 0, 0.3 in age class 1, and 0.5 in age class 2.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] A stable age distribution happens when birth and death rates remain the same over time.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This creates a steady, balanced number of individuals in each age group.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] The age class structure will look like a rectangle when shown in a population pyramid, meaning there is a similar number of individuals in each age range.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] An unstable age distribution happens when birth or death rates change significantly, causing the number of individuals in each age group to shift.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This can make the population chart look uneven - like a triangle or an inverted triangle - showing that some age groups have many more or fewer individuals than others.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] For example, when managing a population of white tail deer targeting a specific age and sex can alter the population pyramid type to either increase, decrease, or stabilize population growth.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] If you start off with a rapid growth age class structure, then targeting the juveniles who are not reproductive yet will help stabilize the population to a slower growth or no growth.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This will make the number of juvenile females to closer the number of females who are aging out of the reproductive age.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Targeting a specific sex will also alter the age class data.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] If looking to reduce the population then targeting hunting efforts on females will have a more impactful change.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Removal of older individuals and males will increase the population by opening up resources for reproductive females and juveniles.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Age can be determined by counting growth rings in fish scales, otoliths, cross-sections of fin spines for species with thick spines such as triggerfish, or teeth for a few species.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Each method has its merits and drawbacks.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Fish scales are easiest to obtain, but may be unreliable if scales have fallen off the fish and new ones grown in their places.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Fin spines may be unreliable for the same reason, and most fish do not have spines of sufficient thickness for clear rings to be visible.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Otoliths will have stayed with the fish throughout its life history, but obtaining them requires killing the fish.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Also, otoliths often require more preparation before ageing can occur.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] An example of using age class structure to learn about a population is a regular bell curve for the population of 1-5 year-old fish with a very low population for the 3-year-olds.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] An age class structure with gaps in population size like the one described earlier implies a bad spawning year 3 years ago in that species.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Often fish in younger age class structures have very low numbers because they were small enough to slip through the sampling nets, and may in fact have a very healthy population.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This could skew class structure data and result in imaccurate management techniques.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Growing evidence suggests temporal shifts in body size, often studied with respect to climate and Bergmann's rule, may be explained by shifts in the age structure of a population.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Because individuals change in size and shape as they age, changes in age class structure can result in shifts in the morphospace of a population reflecting either a greater proportion of older (and larger) or younger (and smaller) individuals.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Aging trees is performed through several methods, the first being to count the trees annual growth rings and the second is to calculate using the growth factor and circumference.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] After a wildfire, depending on the severity, some of the forest will experience a loss in the population of several species.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This interference can drastically alter an age class structure.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] If the fire was low intensity and burned low to the ground killing only young trees, then the age structure would be heavily skewed towards having many older mature trees and very few young trees.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] Wild fires can alter age class structures by removing individuals in certain age classes and altering the type of population pyramid the species is experiencing.
[src:trophic-cascade/age-class-structure] This shift in age class structures can also help predict how quickly the forest will rebound from the disturbance.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based models have many applications in biology, primarily due to the characteristics of the modeling method.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling is a rule-based, computational modeling methodology that focuses on rules and interactions among the individual components or the agents of the matrix .
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The goal of this modeling method is to generate populations of the system components of interest and simulate their interactions in a virtual world.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based models start with rules for behavior and seek to reconstruct, through computational instantiation of those behavioral rules, the observed patterns of behavior.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The behavior of an agent-based model is defined by the rules of its agents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Existing agent rules can be modified or new agents can be added without having to modify the entire model.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Through the use of the individual agents that interact locally with rules of behavior, agent-based models result in a synergy that leads to a higher level whole with much more intricate behavior than those of each individual agent.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Either by excluding non-essential details or when details are not available, agent-based models can be constructed in the absence of complete knowledge of the system under study.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] This allows the model to be as simple and verifiable as possible.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Biological systems exhibit behavior that appears to be random.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The probability of a particular behavior can be determined for a system as a whole and then be translated into rules for the individual agents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In an ecological context, agent-based modeling can be used to model the behaviour of different species such as insects infestations, other invasive species, aphids, aquatic populations, and the evolution of innate foraging behaviors.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling has been used to simulate attack behavior of the mountain pine beetle (MPB), *Dendroctonus ponderosae*, in order to evaluate how different harvesting policies influence spatial characteristics of the forest and spatial propagation of the MPB infestation over time.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] About two-thirds of the land in British Columbia, Canada is covered by forests that are constantly being modified by natural disturbances such as fire, disease, and insect infestation.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Forest resources make up approximately 15% of the province's economy, so infestations caused by insects such as the MPB can have significant impacts on the economy.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB outbreaks are considered a major natural disturbance that can result in widespread mortality of the lodgepole pine tree, one of the most abundant commercial tree species in British Columbia.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Insect outbreaks have resulted in the death of trees over areas of several thousand square kilometers.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model developed for this study was designed to simulate the MPB attack behavior in order to evaluate how management practices influence the spatial distribution and patterns of insect population and their preferences for attacked and killed trees.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Three management strategies were considered by the model: 1) no management, 2) sanitation harvest and 3) salvage harvest.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In the model, the Beetle Agent represented the MPB behavior; the Pine Agent represented the forest environment and tree health evolution; the Forest Management Agent represented the different management strategies.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Beetle Agent follows a series of rules to decide where to fly within the forest and to select a healthy tree to attack, feed, and breed.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB typically kills host trees in its natural environment in order to successfully reproduce.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The beetle larvae feed on the inner bark of mature host trees, eventually killing them.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In order for the beetles to reproduce, the host tree must be sufficiently large and have thick inner bark.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The MPB outbreaks end when the food supply decreases to the point that there is not enough to sustain the population or when climatic conditions become unfavorable for the beetle.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Pine Agent simulates the resistance of the host tree, specifically the Lodgepole pine tree, and monitors the state and attributes of each stand of trees.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] At some point in the MPB attack, the number of beetles per tree reaches the host tree capacity.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] When this point is reached, the beetles release a chemical to direct beetles to attack other trees.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Pine Agent models this behavior by calculating the beetle population density per stand and passes the information to the Beetle Agents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The Forest Management Agent was used, at the stand level, to simulate two common silviculture practices (sanitation and salvage) as well as the strategy where no management practice was employed.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] With the sanitation harvest strategy, if a stand has an infestation rate greater than a set threshold, the stand is removed as well as any healthy neighbor stand when the average size of the trees exceeded a set threshold.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] For the salvage harvest strategy, a stand is removed even it is not under a MPB attack if a predetermined number of neighboring stands are under a MPB attack.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study considered a forested area in the North-Central Interior of British Columbia of approximately 560 hectare.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The area consisted primarily of Lodgepole pine with smaller proportions of Douglas fir and White spruce.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was executed for five time steps, each step representing a single year.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Thirty simulation runs were conducted for each forest management strategy considered.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the simulation showed that when no management strategy was employed, the highest overall MPB infestation occurred.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results also showed that the salvage harvest management technique resulted in a 25% reduction in the number of forest strands killed by the MPB, as opposed to a 19% reduction by the sanitation harvest management strategy.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In summary, the results show that the model can be used as a tool to build forest management policies.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Invasive species refers to "non-native" plants and animals that adversely affect the environments they invade.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The introduction of invasive species may have environmental, economic, and ecological implications.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model developed for the study considered three types of agents: invasive species, importers, and border enforcement agents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In the model, the invasive species can only react to their surroundings, while the importers and border enforcement agents are able to make their own decisions based on their own goals and objectives.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The invasive species has the ability to determine if it has been released in an area containing the target crop, and to spread to adjacent plots of the target crop.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model incorporates spatial probability maps that are used to determine if an invasive species becomes established.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study focused on shipments of broccoli from Mexico into California through the ports of entry Calexico, California and Otay Mesa, California.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The selected invasive species of concern was the crucifer flea beetle (*Phyllotreta cruciferae*).
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] California is by far the largest producer of broccoli in the United States and so the concern and potential impact of an invasive species introduction through the chosen ports of entry is significant.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model also incorporated a spatially explicit damage function that was used to model invasive species damage in a realistic manner.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling provides the ability to analyze the behavior of heterogeneous actors, so three different types of importers were considered that differed in terms of commodity infection rates (high, medium, and low), pretreatment choice, and cost of transportation to the ports.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model gave predictions on inspection rates for each port of entry and importer and determined the success rate of border agent inspection, not only for each port and importer but also for each potential level of pretreatment (no pretreatment, level one, level two, and level three).
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented and ran in NetLogo, version 3.1.5.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Spatial information on the location of the ports of entry, major highways, and transportation routes was included in the analysis as well as a map of California broccoli crops layered with invasive species establishment probability maps.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] BehaviorSpace, a software tool integrated with NetLogo, was used to test the effects of different parameters (e.g. shipment value, pretreatment cost) in the model.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] On average, 100 iterations were calculated at each level of the parameter being used, where an iteration represented a one-year run.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the model showed that as inspection efforts increase, importers increase due care, or the pretreatment of shipments, and the total monetary loss of California crops decreases.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model showed that importers respond to an increase in inspection effort in different ways.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Some importers responded to increased inspection rate by increasing pretreatment effort, while others chose to avoid shipping to a specific port, or shopped for another port.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Another interesting outcome of the model is that when inspectors were not able to learn to respond to an importer with previously infested shipments, damage to California broccoli crops was estimated to be $150 million.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, when inspectors were able to increase inspection rates of importers with previous violations, damage to the California broccoli crops was reduced by approximately 12%.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model provides a mechanism to predict the introduction of invasive species from agricultural imports and their likely damage.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Equally as important, the model provides policy makers and border control agencies with a tool that can be used to determine the best allocation of inspectional resources.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based model can be used to study the population dynamics of the bird cherry-oat aphid, *Rhopalosiphum padi*.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study was conducted in a five square kilometer region of North Yorkshire, a county located in the Yorkshire and the Humber region of England.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based modeling method was chosen because of its focus on the behavior of the individual agents rather than the population as a whole.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The authors propose that traditional models that focus on populations as a whole do not take into account the complexity of the concurrent interactions in ecosystems, such as reproduction and competition for resources which may have significant impacts on population trends.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based modeling approach also allows modelers to create more generic and modular models that are more flexible and easier to maintain than modeling approaches that focus on the population as a whole.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Other proposed advantages of agent-based models include realistic representation of a phenomenon of interest due to the interactions of a group of autonomous agents, and the capability to integrate quantitative variables, differential equations, and rule based behavior into the same model.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented in the modeling toolkit Repast using the JAVA programming language.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was run in daily time steps and focused on the autumn and winter seasons.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Input data for the model included habitat data, daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures, and wind speed and direction.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] For the Aphid agents, age, position, and morphology (alate or apterous) were considered.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Age ranged from 0.00 to 2.00, with 1.00 being the point at which the agent becomes an adult.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Reproduction by the Aphid agents is dependent on age, morphology, and daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Once nymphs hatch, they remain in the same location as their parents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The morphology of the nymphs is related to population density and the nutrient quality of the aphid's food source.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model also considered mortality among the Aphid agents, which is dependent on age, temperatures, and quality of habitat.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The speed at which an Aphid agent ages is determined by the daily minimum, maximum, and mean temperatures.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model considered movement of the Aphid agents to occur in two separate phases, a migratory phase and a foraging phase, both of which affect the overall population distribution.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study started the simulation run with an initial population of 10,000 alate aphids distributed across a grid of 25 meter cells.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The simulation results showed that there were two major population peaks, the first in early autumn due to an influx of alate immigrants and the second due to lower temperatures later in the year and a lack of immigrants.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Ultimately, it is the goal of the researchers to adapt this model to simulate broader ecosystems and animal types.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] A model is proposed to study the population dynamics of two species of macrophytes.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Aquatic plants play a vital role in the ecosystems in which they live as they may provide shelter and food for other aquatic organisms.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, they may also have harmful impacts such as the excessive growth of non-native plants or eutrophication of the lakes in which they live leading to anoxic conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Given these possibilities, it is important to understand how the environment and other organisms affect the growth of these aquatic plants to allow mitigation or prevention of these harmful impacts.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The area of interest in the model was a lake in the Netherlands named Lake Veluwe.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] It is a relatively shallow lake with an average depth of 1.55 meters and covers about 30 square kilometers.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The lake is under eutrophication stress which means that nutrients are not a limiting factor for either of the plant agents in the model.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The initial position of the plant agents in the model was randomly determined.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was implemented using Repast software package and was executed to simulate the growth and decay of the two different plant agents, taking into account the environmental agents previously discussed as well as interactions with other plant agents.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The results of the model execution show that the population distribution of *Chara aspera* has a spatial pattern very similar to the GIS maps of observed distributions.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The authors of the study conclude that the agent rules developed in the study are reasonable to simulate the spatial pattern of macrophyte growth in this particular lake.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Agent-based modeling is increasingly used to model the behaviour of individual cells within a tissue.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] These models are divided into on- and off-lattice models with on-lattice models such as cellular automata and cellular potts model and off-lattice models such as center-based models, vertex-based models, immersed boundary method models and models based on the subcellular element method.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based model can be used model the colonisation of bacteria onto a surface, leading to the formation of biofilms.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Examining such formations is important in soil and river studies, dental hygiene studies, infectious disease and medical implant related infection research, and for understanding biocorrosion.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] An agent-based modelling paradigm was employed to make it possible to explore how each individual bacterium, of a particular species, contributes to the development of the biofilm.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The initial illustration of iDynoMiCS considered how environmentally fluctuating oxygen availability affects the diversity and composition of a community of denitrifying bacteria that induce the denitrification pathway under anoxic or low oxygen conditions.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The study explores the hypothesis that the existence of diverse strategies of denitrification in an environment can be explained by solely assuming that faster response incurs a higher cost.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The agent-based model suggests that if metabolic pathways can be switched without cost the faster the switching the better.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] However, where faster switching incurs a higher cost, there is a strategy with optimal response time for any frequency of environmental fluctuations.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] This suggests that different types of denitrifying strategies win in different biological environments.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Since this introduction the applications of iDynoMiCS continues to increase: a recent exploration of the plasmid invasion in biofilms being one example.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] This study explored the hypothesis that poor plasmid spread in biofilms is caused by a dependence of conjugation on the growth rate of the plasmid donor agent.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Through simulation, the paper suggests that plasmid invasion into a resident biofilm is only limited when plasmid transfer depends on growth.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Sensitivity analysis techniques were employed that suggests parameters relating to timing (lag before plasmid transfer between agents) and spatial reach are more important for plasmid invasion into a biofilm than the receiving agents growth rate or probability of segregational loss.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Further examples that use iDynoMiCS continue to be published, including use of iDynoMiCS in modelling of a *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* biofilm with glucose substrate.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] iDynoMiCS has been developed by an international team of researchers in order to provide a common platform for further development of all individual-based models of microbial biofilms and such like.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was originally the result of years of work by Laurent Lardon, Brian Merkey, and Jan-Ulrich Kreft, with code contributions from Joao Xavier.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] With additional funding from the National Centre for Replacement, Refinement, and Reduction of Animals in Research (NC3Rs) in 2013, the development of iDynoMiCS as a tool for biological exploration continues apace, with new features being added when appropriate.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] From its inception, the team have committed to releasing iDynoMiCS as an open source platform, encouraging collaborators to develop additional functionality that can then be merged into the next stable release.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] IDynoMiCS has been implemented in the Java programming language, with MATLAB and R scripts provided to analyse results.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Biofilm structures that are formed in simulation can be viewed as a movie using POV-Ray files that are generated as the simulation is run.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Experiments have shown that exposure to ionizing irradiation of pubertal mammary glands results in an increase in the ratio of mammary stem cells in the gland.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] This is important because stem cells are thought to be key targets for cancer initiation by ionizing radiation because they have the greatest long-term proliferative potential and mutagenic events persist in multiple daughter cells.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Additionally, epidemiology data show that children exposed to ionizing radiation have a substantially greater breast cancer risk than adults.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The first agent-based model is a multiscale model of mammary gland development starting with a rudimentary mammary ductal tree at the onset of puberty (during active proliferation) all the way to a full mammary gland at adulthood (when there is little proliferation).
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model consists of millions of agents, with each agent representing a mammary stem cell, a progenitor cell, or a differentiated cell in the breast.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Simulations were first run on the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory Lawrencium supercomputer to parameterize and benchmark the model against a variety of *in vivo* mammary gland measurements.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The model was then used to test the three different mechanisms to determine which one led to simulation results that matched *in vivo* experiments the best.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Surprisingly, radiation-induced cell inactivation by death did not contribute to increased stem cell frequency independently of the dose delivered in the model.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Instead the model revealed that the combination of increased self-renewal and cell proliferation during puberty led to stem cell enrichment.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] In contrast epithelial-mesenchymal transition in the model was shown to increase stem cell frequency not only in pubertal mammary glands but also in adult glands.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] This latter prediction, however, contradicted the *in vivo* data; irradiation of adult mammary glands did not lead to increased stem cell frequency.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] These simulations therefore suggested self-renewal as the primary mechanism behind pubertal stem cell increase.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] To further evaluate self-renewal as the mechanism, a second agent-based model was created to simulate the growth dynamics of human mammary epithelial cells (containing stem/progenitor and differentiated cell subpopulations) *in vitro* after irradiation.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] By comparing the simulation results with data from the *in vitro* experiments, the second agent-based model further confirmed that cells must extensively proliferate to observe a self-renewal dependent increase in stem/progenitor cell numbers after irradiation.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] The combination of the two agent-based models and the *in vitro*/*in vivo* experiments provide insight into why children exposed to ionizing radiation have a substantially greater breast cancer risk than adults.
[src:trophic-cascade/agent-based-model-in-biology] Together, they support the hypothesis that the breast is susceptible to a transient increase in stem cell self-renewal when exposed to radiation during puberty, which primes the adult tissue to develop cancer decades later.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The trophic cascade is an ecological concept which has stimulated new research in many areas of ecology.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] For example, it can be important for understanding the knock-on effects of removing top predators from food webs, as humans have done in many places through hunting and fishing.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] A **top-down cascade** is a trophic cascade where the top consumer/predator controls the primary consumer population.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In turn, the primary producer population thrives.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The removal of the top predator can alter the food web dynamics.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In this case, the primary consumers would overpopulate and exploit the primary producers.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Eventually there would not be enough primary producers to sustain the consumer population.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Top-down food web stability depends on competition and predation in the higher trophic levels.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Invasive species can also alter this cascade by removing or becoming a top predator.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This interaction may not always be negative.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Studies have shown that certain invasive species have begun to shift cascades; and as a consequence, ecosystem degradation has been repaired.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] For example, if the abundance of large piscivorous fish is increased in a lake, the abundance of their prey, smaller fish that eat zooplankton, should decrease.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The resulting increase in zooplankton should, in turn, cause the biomass of its prey, phytoplankton, to decrease.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In a **bottom-up cascade**, the population of primary producers will always control the increase/decrease of the energy in the higher trophic levels.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Primary producers are plants and phytoplankton that require photosynthesis.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Although light is important, primary producer populations are altered by the amount of nutrients in the system.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This food web relies on the availability and limitation of resources.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] All populations will experience growth if there is initially a large amount of nutrients.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In a **subsidy cascade**, species populations at one trophic level can be supplemented by external food.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] For example, native animals can forage on resources that don't originate in their same habitat, such as native predators eating livestock.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This may increase their local abundances thereby affecting other species in the ecosystem and causing an ecological cascade.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] (2017) found that native animals living in protected primary rainforest in Malaysia found food subsidies in neighboring oil palm plantations.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This subsidy allowed native animal populations to increase, which then triggered powerful secondary 'cascading' effects on forest tree community.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Specifically, crop-raiding wild boar (*Sus scrofa*) built thousands of nests from the forest understory vegetation and this caused a 62% decline in forest tree sapling density over a 24-year study period.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Such cross-boundary subsidy cascades may be widespread in both terrestrial and marine ecosystems and present significant conservation challenges.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] These trophic interactions shape patterns of biodiversity globally.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Humans and climate change have affected these cascades drastically.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] One example can be seen with sea otters (*Enhydra lutris*) on the Pacific coast of the United States of America.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Over time, human interactions caused a removal of sea otters.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] One of their main prey, the Pacific purple sea urchin (*Strongylocentrotus purpuratus*) eventually began to overpopulate.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The overpopulation caused increased predation of giant kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*).
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] As a result, there was extreme deterioration of the kelp forests along the California coast.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This is why it is important for countries to regulate marine and terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Predator-induced interactions could heavily influence the flux of atmospheric carbon if managed on a global scale.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] For example, a study was conducted to determine the cost of potential stored carbon in living kelp biomass in sea otter (*Enhydra lutris*) enhanced ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The study valued the potential storage between US$205 million and US$408 million on the European Carbon Exchange (2012).
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Aldo Leopold is generally credited with first describing the mechanism of a trophic cascade, based on his observations of overgrazing of mountain slopes by deer after human extermination of wolves.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Slobodkin are generally credited with introducing the concept into scientific discourse, although they did not use the term either.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Hairston, Smith and Slobodkin argued that predators reduce the abundance of herbivores, allowing plants to flourish.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This is often referred to as the green world hypothesis.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The green world hypothesis is credited with bringing attention to the role of top-down forces (e.g. predation) and indirect effects in shaping ecological communities.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The prevailing view of communities prior to Hairston, Smith and Slobodkin was trophodynamics, which attempted to explain the structure of communities using only bottom-up forces (e.g. resource limitation).
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Smith may have been inspired by the experiments of a Czech ecologist, Hrbáček, whom he met on a United States State Department cultural exchange.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Hrbáček had shown that fish in artificial ponds reduced the abundance of zooplankton, leading to an increase in the abundance of phytoplankton.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Hairston, Smith and Slobodkin feuded that the ecological communities acted as food chains with three trophic levels.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Subsequent models expanded the argument to food chains with more than or fewer than three trophic levels.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Additionally, he argued that the number of trophic levels in a food chain increases as the productivity of the ecosystem increases.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Although Hairston, Smith and Slobodkin formulated their argument in terms of terrestrial food chains, the earliest empirical demonstrations of trophic cascades came from marine and, especially, aquatic ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The fact that the earliest documented trophic cascades all occurred in lakes and streams led a scientist to speculate that fundamental differences between aquatic and terrestrial food webs made trophic cascades primarily an aquatic phenomenon.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Trophic cascades were restricted to communities with relatively low species diversity, in which a small number of species could have overwhelming influence and the food web could operate as a linear food chain.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Additionally, well documented trophic cascades at that point in time all occurred in food chains with algae as the primary producer.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Trophic cascades, Strong argued, may only occur in communities with fast-growing producers which lack defenses against herbivory.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Critics pointed out that published terrestrial trophic cascades generally involved smaller subsets of the food web (often only a single plant species).
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] This was quite different from aquatic trophic cascades, in which the biomass of producers as a whole were reduced when predators were removed.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Additionally, most terrestrial trophic cascades did not demonstrate reduced plant biomass when predators were removed, but only increased plant damage from herbivores.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] It was unclear if such damage would actually result in reduced plant biomass or abundance.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In 2002 a meta-analysis found trophic cascades to be generally *weaker* in terrestrial ecosystems, meaning that changes in predator biomass resulted in smaller changes in plant biomass.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In contrast, a study published in 2009 demonstrated that multiple species of trees with highly varying autecologies are in fact heavily impacted by the loss of an apex predator.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Both the exterpation of gray wolves (*Canis lupus*) in Yellowstone National Park, complete by about 1930, and the reintroduction of them in 1995 and 1996 was followed by dramatic changes throughout trophic cascades.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Freed from wolf predation, expanding elk herds reduced stands of aspen (*Populus tremuloides*), cottonwoods (*Populus* spp.), and willows (*Salix* spp.), and eliminated riparian plant and animal communities including beaver colonies.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Ecological changes since the reintroduction of the wolves have been highly variable in time and space throughout Yellowstone.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The following paragraphs focus on the Northern Range of the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Some of the decreases in plants and animals listed above have been locally reversed after the wolf reintroduction.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] But the ecosystem as a whole has not completely reverted to its state before the exterpation of wolves.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The pre-1930 Northern Range ecosystem has been characterized as a "*beaver-willow state*." It changed into an "*elk-grassland state*" after the elimination of the wolves.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Post wolf reintroduction, much of the Northern Range has not reverted to the beaver willow state but remains in the elk-grassland state.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Such lack of return to a prior state is referred to as hysteresis.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The principal mechanism of hysteresis in the Northern Range is creek and river incision.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The elimination of beavers - and hence their dams - caused increased creek flow rates and erosion.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Creek beds were lowered and with them the water table adjacent to the creek.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] These conditions are unfavorable for willow growth and hence beavers.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] A rare controlled *in-situ* experiment established that only the fencing out of herbivores combined with human-made "beaver" dams allowed willows to reestablish themselves.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The mere fencing out of ungulates was insufficient.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] A complex analysis of 21 years of observations of wolves, elk and aspen in the Northern Range concluded that "trait-mediated indirect effects," changes in elk behavior triggered by the wolves, can be ignored in the understanding of the local trophic cascades.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The reintroduction and subsequent increasing numbers of Yellowstone wolves were paralleled by an increase in grizzly bears (*Ursus arctos horribilis*) which had been mismanaged by the National Park Service.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Likewise, cougars (*Puma concolor**)*** became more abundant.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] The Northern Range elk herd seasonally migrates between the park and adjacent areas in Montana where they are subject to regulated human hunting.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Further accounting for predation by black bears, five top preditors contribute to the trophic cascade in the Northern Range, human hunters, wolves, cougars and grizzly and black bears.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Trophic cascades also impact the biodiversity of ecosystems.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] In examples from Yellowstone National Park, scavengers, such as ravens (*Corvus corax*), bald eagles (*Haliaeetus leucocephalus*), grizzly bears (*Ursus arctos horribilis*) and others are subsidized by the carcasses of wolf kills.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Willow habitat restored thanks to the reintroduced wolves has benefited song bird species.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Bison (*Bison bison*) numbers in the northern range have been steadily increasing as elk numbers have declined, presumably due to a decrease in interspecific competition between the two species.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Although the existence of trophic cascades is not controversial, ecologists have long debated how ubiquitous they are.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Hairston, Smith and Slobodkin argued that terrestrial ecosystems, as a rule, behave as a three trophic level trophic cascade, which provoked immediate controversy.
[src:trophic-cascade/trophic-cascade] Antagonistically, this principle is sometimes called the "trophic trickle".
